  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international framework established\n- Initial focus on financial reporting requirements\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed international anti-money laundering standards\n- Recommended comprehensive regulatory approaches\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986, US)\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (2002, UK)\n- Enhanced international cooperation mechanisms\n- Expanded legal definitions of money laundering\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Comprehensive customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced electronic transaction monitoring\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n\n5. Recent Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency transactions\n- Digital platform monitoring\n- Advanced data analytics for detecting complex laundering schemes\n\n6. Global Coordination\n- Increased information sharing between jurisdictions\n- Synchronized regulatory frameworks\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislative landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
